40 2021-02-25 nervousness Within one minute of receiving vaccine, the patient became pale, stated that he felt dizzy and faint... Read more
Close
Within one minute of receiving vaccine, the patient became pale, stated that he felt dizzy and fainted. Patient regained consciousness within one minute. Upon regaining consciousness, patient reported feeling lightheaded and dizzy but was oriented to person, place and time. Skin was warm and dry but pale in color. After regaining consciousness, patient also stated that he has a history of fainting 5-6 years ago after receiving an influenza vaccination. (During screening questions, patient denied having any reactions to vaccines in the past) Patient independently moved from a chair to a laying down position on a cot and expressed an improvement in how he was feeling. Vital signs taken after event as recorded below. When asked patient stated that he does recall times when he thinks he may have been hypoglycemic in the past. Patient also states that he has been very nervous about receiving injections throughout his life. EMS called and assessed patient at the vaccination clinic site. Patient drank a 10 oz bottle of orange juice prior to EMS arriving and when EMS staff obtained his blood sugar the result was 97. EMS stated that patient was stable and all vital signs were stable. Patients skin color improved to pink. Patients wife was called by patient and she provided transportation home for patient. Prior to leaving the vaccination clinic, patient was walking around for several minutes and denied any feelings of being lightheaded or dizzy. VITALS SIGNS: 5:06pm: Heart rate: 50, Oxygen Saturation: 99% on room air 5:15 pm: Blood pressure: 100/78 ; Heart rate: 50; oxygen saturation 99% on room air. 5:20pm: Blood pressure 98/76 Heart rate:52; oxygen saturation 96% on room air. 5:34 pm: Blood pressure 92/68 Heart rate: 53 oxygen saturation 97% on room air. Vital signs taken by EMS staff were not recorded by public health nursing staff.

Patient felt to be in distress at the close of his observation time. He was complaining of trouble with focusing his eyes, left sided chest pain, and was diaphoretic. Pt appeared to be in moderate distress and very anxious. I examined the pt through the car window and listened to his heart and lungs. Pt was not in respiratory distress and heart rate and rhythm were regular. Reassurance was provided to the pt, but he was also told that to be safe I recommended that he be evaluated in the emergency department and that he be transported via ambulance. Pt expressed understanding and agreed to going to the ED but was refusing transport via EMS. Pt was the passenger in the vehicle and he said that the driver could just take him. I expressed that transport via EMS would be the safest but we could not make him go via EMS and that if they wanted to leave via private vehicle then they could but i still recommended that he be evaluated in the ED. He expressed understanding and that he would go directly to the ED via personal car.

Gen: Awake, Alert, Moderate Distress, diaphoretic Cardio: RRR w/o m/g/r Resp: LCAT in all fields, mildly increased work of breathing Skin: no rashes noted, no edema noted of the face or angioedema noted of the lips Psych: anxious Neuro: able to answer questions appropriately, able to follow instructions, CN 2-12 grossly intact Pt instructed that his symptoms were not necessarily consistent with anaphylaxis but with diaphoresis and left sided CP I recommended that he be evaluated in the Emergency Department. 40 2021-03-16 insomnia, disturbance in attention, feeling abnormal It has been 6 weeks since my 2nd dose of the Moderna vaccine for Covid-19. For the first 3-4 days I ... Read more
Close
It has been 6 weeks since my 2nd dose of the Moderna vaccine for Covid-19. For the first 3-4 days I had the usual moderate flu-like symptoms: dizziness, headaches, fatigue, chills, soreness at vaccine siteetc. Days 5-7 I seemed to gradually improve. On day 8 all of the symptoms returned with greater severity: this time I had a fever, the chills were much more intense, the headaches were excruciating, body and joint aches all over the place--I couldn't sleep or focus on anything cognitively taxing. Interestingly, my brother, who was vaccinated just after me, also had more severe side effects beginning on day 8 post 2nd dose. He improved after 3-4 days, but my recovery has been much much lengthier. By day 14 I was still feeling very ill, though the fever did subside. Sometime in the third week the pain in my arm at the vaccination site returned, then became intermittent, and still bothers me from time to time. I also started getting muscle spasms in the same exact locations that sent me to the ER after my probably bout with Covid in the spring of 2020. Thankfully these lasted only a week or so, though I began feeling muscle soreness in different parts of my body, ever changing. By the 4th week I was slightly better and down to 4 main symptoms: chills (by far the worst of the symptoms--to the point at which my skin would feel like it was being frostbitten by dry ice every time I changed sweaty clothes), occasional splitting headaches, and muscle soreness that included both the injection site on my arm and other areas. I had other symptoms as well, fatigue and brain fog, etc, but these were present before the vaccination, though not as severe.

Close
Initial symptoms of the first shot included injection site pain, neck soreness, and severe headache that would come and go. The next day I was so exhausted I couldn't work for 2 days. I barely got out of bed until about 40 hours after the shot where I was able to get out and do some gardening. The reason I am filling this out was at right around 72 hours after the vaccine, I was laying down watching a YouTube video feeling quite relaxed. I then experienced a tachycardia event where my heart rate went up to 120 and stayed there for about an hour. I remained calm and was not experiencing anxiety, but the heart rate persisted. I have had this happen before in panic attacks, but it's quite rare and I am in acute, high level stress. Almost 2 weeks later to the day, I had another tachycardia, stronger than any I've had my entire life that only lasted about 7 seconds, but I would estimate my heart rate jumped to over 250. I thought I was going to go into cardiac arrest it was so jarring. I'm not sure if that one was related to the vaccine.

The occurrence of additional non-serious events is detailed below. The patient's past medical history included Chronic fatigue syndrome, Fibromyalgia and Neurocardiogenic syncope. On 13-Jan-2021, the patient received first dose of mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (Intramuscular) 1 dosage form. On 10-Feb-2021, received second dose of mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (Intramuscular) dosage was changed to 1 dosage form. On 01-Feb-2021, the patient experienced DIZZINESS (dizzy.). On 10-Feb-2021, the patient experienced ARTHRALGIA (joint pains), CHILLS (chills) and PYREXIA (mild fever). In February 2021, the patient experienced FEELING ABNORMAL ("feels like my body has been split into 1000 different microclimates). On 18-Feb-2021, the patient experienced ARRHYTHMIA (arrhythmias) (seriousness criterion medically significant), PAROSMIA (altered smell), PALPITATIONS (heart rhythm, palpitations), TACHYCARDIA (tachycardia), PHOTOSENSITIVITY REACTION (become sensitive to light and cannot go outside without sunglasses), HYPERHIDROSIS (sweating more especially acidic and disgusting), HEADACHE (splitting headaches) and VACCINATION SITE PAIN (pain in the left arm at the vaccination site). On an unknown date, the patient experienced EXTRASYSTOLES (missed beats). On 14-Feb-2021, ARTHRALGIA (joint pains) and CHILLS (chills) had resolved. On 24-Feb-2021, HEADACHE (splitting headaches) had resolved. At the time of the report, ARRHYTHMIA (arrhythmias), PAROSMIA (altered smell), FEELING ABNORMAL ("feels like my body has been split into 1000 different microclimates), DIZZINESS (dizzy.), PALPITATIONS (heart rhythm, palpitations), TACHYCARDIA (tachycardia), EXTRASYSTOLES (missed beats), PHOTOSENSITIVITY REACTION (become sensitive to light and cannot go outside without sunglasses), HYPERHIDROSIS (sweating more especially acidic and disgusting), VACCINATION SITE PAIN (pain in the left arm at the vaccination site) and PYREXIA (mild fever) outcome was unknown. No concomitant medications were provided. Treatment taken were Diphenhydramine (Benadryl) , Ibuprofen (Advil), Prednisone and acupuncture to alleviate the symptoms experienced. Dizzy; short term memory sucks and it's frustrating; Can't see well; Fibromyalgia; bone pain; Neuropathy; Feeling aches in the body; Bells palsy-paralysis on the left side of the face/ pressure on the left side of the face and neck; headache; Ringing in the ears; Pressure in the ears; A spontaneous report was received from consumer concerning a 41-year-old, male patient who received Moderna's COVID-19 vaccine (mRNA-1273) and experienced pressure in ears/ear discomfort, ringing in ears/tinnitus, pressure on the left side of the face and neck which was found to be Bell's Palsy/facial paralysis, Headache, neuropathy peripheral, fibromyalgia, memory impairment, couldn't see well/visual decrease, feeling aches in the body/myalgia, and dizziness. The patient's medical history included neuropathy and fibromyalgia and past cancer. No relevant concomitant medications were reported. On 03 Feb 2021, the patient received the first of two doses of mRNA-1273 (Lot number: 028L20A) intramuscularly for prophylaxis of COVID-19 infection. On 24FEB2021 the patient began experiencing pressure and a ringing in the ears and then started like a pressure on the left side of the face and neck. On 25FEB2021, the patient started having a headache and on 26FEB2021 the paralysis on the left side of the face began. The patient said that it worsened, couldn't eat, couldn't speak, and went to the hospital. The patient said that they had a CT Scan, and the result was that it wasn't a stroke. Vitals were taken and blood work came back normal. The conclusion was Bell's Palsy. The patient stated that they couldn't see well and were dizzy. The patient said that they were experiencing fibromyalgia and neuropathy that they had when they had cancer. The patient also mentioned that they were experiencing some bone pain and that their short term memory was not good and was frustrating. Treatment of these events were not reported. The outcome of the events, ear discomfort, tinnitus, facial paralysis, headache, neuropathy peripheral, fibromyalgia, memory impairment, visual decrease, myalgia and dizziness were considered unknown.; Reporter's Comments: Based on the current available information and temporal association between the use of the product and the start date of the event, a causal relationship cannot be excluded. The patient's medical history of neuropathy, fibromyalgia and past history of cancer remains the contributing factors. Further information has been requested.

After vaccination, I went to ER on Jan 15, 2021 at around 11:30PM due to severe back pain and was diagnosed with pleurisy through X-ray. My X-ray also showed an enlarged heart but I suspect that was due to the fact that I could not breath properly when the x-ray was taken. I will repeat the X-ray in a couple of weeks. 42 2021-04-25 sleep disorder On 4/22/21, approximately 1 hr after the Moderna COVID-19 first vaccination injection, I started to ... Read more
Close
On 4/22/21, approximately 1 hr after the Moderna COVID-19 first vaccination injection, I started to encounter allergic reactions that I used to suffer about 20 years ago. My air intake decreased, and my skin began to become irritated. I formerly had environmental allergies that would reduce my air intake, and the first place I noticed the effects were on my skin and I would become irritable. Physicians told me that when my oxygen levels were low, the body would channel the air to where it was most needed, which is generally not the skin, so my skin would become irritated. When this used to occur, I would respond involuntarily with facial twitches and pulling at my face and hair. Physicians explained that these twitches and pulling actions would draw air to the surface of my skin where I was air depleted. When I took the Moderna injection, this happened again -- I found myself with low air, my face was twitching, and I was pulling on my face to draw air to the area. The result when I was 19 and dealing with allergies is that I would remove small patches of hair from my head or eyebrows or eyelashes, and this would happen almost unconsciously as I tried to stimulate the areas and draw air to the surface of my skin. I did the same thing on 4/22/21, and found later, when looking into a mirror, that I had removed a section of my eyebrow unconsciously. It all comes back to oxygen depletion. A different and more intense event occurred in the night of Friday, 4/23/21, and the early morning of Saturday, 4/24/21. I went to bed at about 11 p.m. or 11:30 p.m. Between that time and approximately 1:30 a.m., I had difficulty sleeping, and I dreamed of pain in my chest. I finally woke up about 1:30 a.m. and found the pain in my chest was real. I was having difficulty breathing deeply. It felt as if the lower part of my lungs (at least on one side) was solidifying or inaccessible. What I did was begin forcing myself to breathe as deeply as possible. Over a period of 30 minutes or longer, I was able to gradually reclaim the use of the deepest part of my longs. With every forced deep breath, I was able to chip away at the area that felt like it was freezing up. Finally, I felt that I could access the deepest part of my longs and breath normally. The pain and lack of use in my lower lungs were very concerning.

46 2021-02-08 sleep disorder Note: I had a PCR confirmed SARS-CoV-2 infection in March, 2020. Approximately 12 hours after the ... Read more
Close
Note: I had a PCR confirmed SARS-CoV-2 infection in March, 2020. Approximately 12 hours after the second vaccine dose, I experienced intense soreness at the vaccination site (significantly greater than the first dose). In the middle of the night I awoke with flu-like symptoms. At 9am I took acetominophen for fever, rigors, muscle aches. This brought mild relief from approx. 9:45am to 11:15 am. My condition continued to worsen through the early afternoon with rigors and significant generalized muscle aches. I experienced tachycardia (90-105 bpm vs normal of ~70bpm), SOB, and starting measuring pulse oximetry which read from 89%-94% (my usual does not go below 97%). This persisted until approximately 8pm with no improvement. I took 40 mg prednisone, 600 mg ibuprofen and within 3 hours was starting to have symptom resolution. I am a physician and up to date on all my vaccinations. I have never had anything approaching this type of response. I don't know if prior SARS-CoV-2 infection creates a situation were the very potent mRNA vaccine triggers a large immunologic recall response. I wanted to get this noted as there may be some reason to alter the vaccine schedule for prior SARS-CoV-2 infections

Also, as of right now (2:44pm on Sunday 3/21), no kidney stone has passed. I have been urinating into a cup to see if one comes out. 51 2021-04-25 fear State opened Covid vaccines to 50 and over on Mon, March 22. I immediately scheduled my appointment ... Read more
Close
State opened Covid vaccines to 50 and over on Mon, March 22. I immediately scheduled my appointment for a first shot at a Dept of Health site near me for Wed, March 24. I had no immediate negative side effects. When I woke on Fri, March 26 and commenced my day of remote work from home, I noticed my left eye vision was blurry. I proceeded to work that day and continued my normal activities into the weekend assuming my vision would self-correct. By Sunday, March 26, my left eye vision was still noticeably problematic so I scheduled to see an optometrist whom I had seen before. I saw him at 12:15pm on Tues, March 30. After running numerous vision tests, optometrist let me know my vision loss in the left eye seemed to be the result of a stroke that had cut blood flow in the optic nerve and damaged my vision in the lower portions of the left eye. The center and upper portions of my left eye were generally unaffected at that time. He suggested I see my primary care physician to check for vitals, such as blood pressure and do other blood work, and more importantly see a neuro ophthalmologist urgently. The next morning, Wed, March 31 I saw my PCP, who informed me my blood pressure was normal, requested blood work, and gave me a prescription for an MRI of my brain, with and without contrast. I am 6'2" and I weighed at 239, about where it has been for most of last 15 years. I also complained of pain and stiffness in my front right thigh and lower right back. She said if I didn't get an appointment to see a neuro ophthalmologist that same afternoon, she recommended I go to an ER. With the help of Optometrist's office, I was able to get an appointment that day with Dr., neuro ophthalmologist at 2:15pm on Wed, March 31. His office repeated numerous vision tests and confirmed the left eye vision loss (essentially the lower half excluding the center) and diagnosed it as a NAION - non arthritic ischemic optic neuropathy. With this diagnosis, there was no treatment, and I scheduled a follow-up for May 12. He said that my optic nerve into my left eye would slowly reduce its swelling over the next 6 to 8 weeks and in that time, my vision could remain the same, or improve. At that point, I didn't think it would worsen, but sadly that later happened. In addition to the the first MRI that PCP prescribed, Neuro ophthalmologist prescribed a second MRI of orbits, with and without contrast. He also suggested I begin taking a low dose Aspirin daily, which I did. The next week, the blood work revealed a very slightly elevated cholesterol reading. I was told by my PCP on April 5 that this would normally not be considered as a problematic level of high cholesterol, but should be improved or lowered. The blood tests taken at Lab on Fri, April 2 revealed a LDL Chol, Calculated as 111, whereby <100 was considered desirable range. Other than that, there was nothing of concern in my blood work. The two MRIs were done on April 9 and April 20, and did not reveal findings which doctors felt would have impacted my optic nerve swelling or had caused the eye stroke. Out of precaution, I scheduled to see a cardiologist on Tues, April 13. She recommended I start taking Crestor for cholesterol, and do a series of tests which I completed on Friday, April 23 - echocardiogram; holter monitor; transesophageal echocardiogram; and ultrasound carotid bilateral. As of today, Mon, April 26 I do not know the results of the cardio work-up, but both neuro ophthalmologists I saw felt that a problem related to my heart would not have caused this stroke in my eye. Finally, on Fri, April 23 I had a consultation with a second highly recommended neuro ophthalmologist. After a series of vision tests, she agreed with other doctor's diagnosis of NAION - non arthritic ischemic optic neuropathy. She also said there was nothing I could do to treat except wait for the next 4 or more weeks for the optic nerve swelling to go down. She also confirmed my fear which was that my left eye vision had worsened since March 31 as my vision loss was no longer limited to the lower portion of my left eye, but now included blind spots throughout the upper range of my left eye vision, making my loss of peripheral vision worse and more widespread. She said in some cases with NAION, a patient's vision could remain the same, could improve or could worsen in the 6 to 8 weeks after the event. Four weeks after the March 26 event, by April 23 my left eye vision had worsened. I still hold out hope that it can improve some in the next four weeks... My right eye vision was not affected in any way, although one risk of NAION is that there is a 20% (?) chance it may recur in the next 5 years, and if it does, it most commonly affects the other, good eye. None of the doctors I saw directly attributed my vision loss to the Moderna vaccine taken on March 24; however, there has also not been a clear cause determined by my doctors. While most of the doctors I saw seemed to think it coincidental, none also was able to absolutely rule it out either as a cause or a trigger. Dr. suggested I follow through with this idea, which other medical professionals suggested, to submit this vaccine adverse event report. Without a doubt, this was an adverse effect and/or problem that occurred soon after (36 hours approximately) taking the first dose of the Moderna vaccine.

53 2021-05-25 mental status changes Patient manifested with flu-like symptoms (myalgias, fatigue, cough, abdominal discomfort, shortness... Read more
Close
Patient manifested with flu-like symptoms (myalgias, fatigue, cough, abdominal discomfort, shortness of breath) with high-grade fevers (TMax 103F) approximately 4-6 hours following administration of 2nd Moderna vaccine on 5/4/2021 per patient's wife. The symptoms progressively worsened to the point that he presented to an outside hospital on 5/12/2021 at which time he was found to be tachycardic and febrile (T 103.1F). Labs at that time were notable for significant thrombocytopenia, elevated creatinine, elevated lactate, elevated procalcitonin. Chest imaging showed bilateral airspace disease. CT of the abdomen noted hepatosplenomegaly with no evidence of lymphadenopathy. Echocardiogram showed normal cardiac function. He was empirically started on broad-spectrum antibiotics. Labs on 5/13/2021 were notable for a markedly elevated ferritin level, fasting hypertriglyceridemia, elevated CRP, elevated transaminase levels, hyperbilirubinemia, markedly elevated CXCL-9 level, markedly elevated IL-18 level, normal natural killer cell function. Of note, while his blood and urine cultures were negative, he was found to have elevated EBV viral load on peripheral blood draw. He had a bone marrow biopsy which reportedly showed rare evidence of cells with what appeared to be erythrocytes within their cytoplasm, concerning for HLH. Given strong clinical and serological suspicion for HLH, he was transferred to our hospital for a higher level of care. Upon transfer to our facility on 5/18/2021, his inflammatory markers were persistently elevated. He unfortunately developed worsened renal and respiratory failure, and required both hemodialysis and intubation respectively. He was continued on empiric broad-spectrum antibiotics, however we additionally initiated high-dose steroids as well as anakinra for treatment of HLH. Given EBV viremia, we also began rituximab therapy. He was successfully extubated, however as of 5/26/2021 remains dialysis-dependent with continued improvement in urinary output. His post-intubation course has been complicated by encephalopathy of unknown etiology. We have consulted infectious disease to proceed with a diagnostic lumbar puncture to ascertain potential CNS pathogens explaining the cause of his altered mental status. MRI of the brain showed no evidence of pathology. CNS involvement by HLH remains on our differential.

The following is an email the patient wrote to us describing his events: I received Moderna Covid Vaccine on January 4, 2021 and February 1, 2021 at Medical Center in On the evening of January 12, 2021, I arrived home from working as a Pharmacist following a 13 hour shift at Medical Center with no medical complaints. Later that night I experienced a severe coughing, sneezing episode where I was gagging on the mucous. I spit out a bunch of stuff and did a nasal rinse. I took some cold medicine like Certrizine and Mucinex-D. Simultaneously with the coughing episode I developed a tingling sensation on the right side of my body from my neck to my toes. I also noticed that my temperature sensations on my right hand was different from my Left hand. I had gotten a water bottle from my refrigerator that felt room temp to my right hand but was cold when held in the left hand. I was feeling dizzy or drunk and was walking funny. When I tried to walk straight forward I actually drifted to the left as I walked. I was having difficulty swallowing medications, food or liquids. I wondered if was experiencing the onset of Covid Symptoms. I was well enough versed on stroke symptoms to be worried about one sided tingling and altered gait being from a stroke. The flu like nasal symptoms and altered right sided pain and temperature sensations persisted through the night, so I went to the ER at Medical Center the morning of January 13th. The ER worked me over with multiple Covid/Strept/Flu tests, evaluation for possible stroke (with multiple scans and stroke score.) The ERP also evaluated the possibility of Bells Palsy or Guillain Barre secondary to Covid vaccine the week before. The Covid Testing was Negative. The stroke score was low enough NOT to have warranted thrombolytic therapy. The neurological issues did not appear to be Bells palsy or Guillain barre. After the ER Visit I attempted to see a neurologist. May 25, 2021 was the earliest available appointment that I could obtain. The symptoms were not severe enough to prevent me working as a Pharmacist. The altered pain and temperature sensations remain without much improvement even now 4 months later. The Neurologist diagnosed me as having had a stroke, specifically left sided Lateral Medullary Infarct, also known as Wallenburg Syndrome. There have been reports from the other vaccines having caused blood clot issues since my event.

Anxiety, weakness, mild fever, sweating, all pretty mild, but in my opinion should be noted because it felt to me like a hypoglycemic event. As a person with diabetes, I had to take extra finger sticks that day because I did not trust my normal sensation of low blood sugar. I think this is a common reaction to the vaccine, and I intend to get the 2nd dose, but maybe diabetics should be warned about confusing this common reaction with hypoglycemia and cautioned to be extra vigilant with finger sticks the day after receiving the injection.

Initially just mild fatigue and "brain fog" but by the next day the fatigue "brain fog"/malaise/disorientation was so intense I could barely stay awake and could not function at my desk job. This continued at that intensity for about a week. I couldn't do ANYTHING...was previously running 7 miles/day but in the past month since vaccine I have only had the energy to walk around the block one time. The cognitive impairment has been debilitating at work where I can not concentrate or process complex topics. I'm an IT executive so this is part of my daily job and was no problem prior to the vaccine. By the second week I was starting to make very tiny progress each day. I would be OK for an hour or 2 after waking up but then the fatigue and malaise would return and I wouldn't be able to work. This is often accompanied by headache. Generally the duration of symptoms has been getting shorter each day but very slowly. On may 9 my impairment was so great I couldn't even drive (was like being a bit drunk). Finally, Monday May 10, the intensity of the symptoms was light enough that I was able to work a full day despite the mild headache and fog. The same continued on May 11, so I hope I am close to being over this.
55 2021-05-13 anxiety, depression I acquired Covid on January 13. I was sick for three days, largely with headaches. I lost my sense o... Read more
Close
I acquired Covid on January 13. I was sick for three days, largely with headaches. I lost my sense of smell. After approximately 7 weeks, I had recovered most of my sense of smell. I received dose 1 of Moderna on March 2. Four days later I noticed that my sense of smell had diminished substantially. I contacted my primary and was assured that it wasn't a result of the vaccine. I saw an EENT, and he too assured me it wasn't because of the vaccine. I was put on Flonase and one course of steroids (12 days). After 2 weeks, my sense of smell was returning. I received my second dose on 3/30. Within 12 hours I knew something was wrong. My sense of smell seemed to be obliterated. It felt like there was a "hole" in the center of my nose. Within 36 hours, the turbinates in my nose were hypertrophic. I have never suffered seasonal allergies and had never even heard the word "turbinate" before this. 45 days later, my left nostril is blocked. My right nostril is nearly blocked. I have fluid behind both ears, and my hearing has diminshed. I feel completely let down by the medical establishment and even the CDC. There is no way that I should have been advised to have the vaccine just 40 days after contracting covid. All of the promises that the vaccine can't reduce sense of smell because there's no Covid in the vaccine are misleading. My immune system responded to the vaccine by attacking the site of the original infection, which was my nose. This has been devastating to me. I am depressed, anxious, and hopeless that this will correct itself. I will likely suffer some percentage of hearing loss. I was completely recovered from Covid, and it's only these vaccines that have ruined my health.

Patient admitted with high grade AV block, sinus pause, and recurrent syncope. 57-year-old white male with PMH only of cigarette use who notes about 2 weeks of generalized malaise, then in the last 24 hours has had 2 syncopal episodes that were accompanied by diaphoresis only without other prodrome. He got his second dose of Moderna COVID-19 vaccine on 5/28/21, then on the following day had been working in the barn without any dyspnea chest pain or shortness of breath but felt generally fatigued so went to take a nap. He got up to check his temperature, then "just hit the floor". Not preceded by blackout of vision, lightheadedness, chest pain, dyspnea palpitations, nausea but was accompanied by sweats. He believes he was out only briefly, and when he awoke was not confused and did not have tongue biting or loss of bladder or bowel continence. He then got up and went about his day normally, then around 2 AM awoke to let the dogs out and had an identical event, but this time hit his chin on a chain saw on the floor and suffered a laceration. He presented to ED for evaluation where his laceration was sutured. He is hemodynamically stable and afebrile. Initial labs and diagnostics are unrevealing and an EKG showed a normal sinus rhythm without acute or chronic ischemic changes. Noncontrast CT of the head and the face showed no evidence of bony damage, no intracranial bleed or large territory infarct. While in the ED, the patient had a brief bradycardic episode accompanied by diaphoresis although a dedicated strip is not available and it is unclear what his rhythm was. He did not syncopize. Hospitalist service was asked to accept for syncope evaluation. When admitting physician saw patient, he reported feeling completely well without any other issues. He does note he had about 2 weeks of malaise before all of this started and a mild decrease in his ability to work intensely, but had attributed this to cigarette smoking. Review of systems was essentially negative. He is a hobby farmer and has had a couple of tick bites this year. While admitting physician was in the room at the end of the visit, the patient had an episode of diaphoresis and went into a high-grade second-degree AV block with disappearance of atrial activity without ventricular escape and lost consciousness for about a second. No jerking or twitching observed. The episode a couple of seconds then self terminated and the patient awoke and completely recovered mentation and was in a sinus rhythm. He was diaphoretic and felt ill afterward this. He had no chest pain or dyspnea. Immediately after the episode with repeat vitals the patient's heart rate was in the 70s and a normal sinus rhythm and blood pressure is 136/80. Oxygen saturations are preserved. Not on any rate limiting agents either here in emergency department or at home. Patient found to have P-P interval prolongation with AV block and subsequent sinus arrest possibly situational in the setting of coming off of a colonoscopy and receiving second Moderna COVID-19 vaccine. A pacemaker was placed 6/1/2021 without complication and the patient was discharged in stable condition on 6/2/2021.

I almost went to the hospital, but I didn't because I take care of my elderly father and could not leave him by himself. I didn't read about people having my particular side effect, so I thought I was an outlier of sorts. I am filling this out now because there are reports coming out that the Pfizer vaccine may be tied to myocarditis in men, and from the symptoms explained, it seems to line up with what I experienced. Although I had Moderna, not Pfizer, I thought maybe I should report it in case it is a generic "mrna vaccine" issue.

Fever, confusion. He received the vaccine about 10:30 AM. He worked in the yard during the day and seemed to be doing fine. After eating dinner, he seemed to be unusually drowsy. Over the course of the evening, the wife realized that he was very confused and was too weak to ambulate. She summoned EMS, and he was taken to ED. Of note, he had an episode of confusion lasting several days in 2/2021. No fever at that time. Evaluated in ED on 2/20/2021. CT Head and labs unrevealing. Released to home. Initial vital signs 4/30/2021 at 00:59: Temperature-100.4, blood pressure-133/68, pulse-110, respirations-18, room air O2 saturation-97%. He subsequently had a T-max of 102.8. He received empiric therapy with dexamethasone, vancomycin, ceftriaxone, ampicillin, acyclovir on the evening of 4/30. The morning of 5/1 he was afebrile, alert, oriented x3. Steroids and anti-infective discontinued. He was observed in the hospital for another 24 hours and had no recurrence of fever, confusion.

I heard the second dose might give more of an adverse reaction than the first but I felt I needed to report what happened to me because of how bad it was. After about 9 hours from getting the shot I got a headache that turned in to the worst migraine I've ever had in my life that lasted over 30 hours. I had a fever that ranged from 101F to 103F that has lasted for more than 30 hours, I also developed severe muscle and joint pain so much so that I could only get out of bed to go to the bathroom and that was with great pain. I also have had nausea that has lasted over 36 hours. I took Tylenol (1000mg) every few hours, 4 times with out relief. I also took a Tramadol which helped a little with the pain but then my fever spiked for a few hours.
